{"batchcomplete":"","query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Trauma_trigger","to":"Trauma trigger"}],"pages":{"14817978":{"pageid":14817978,"ns":0,"title":"Trauma trigger","revisions":[{"contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"A '''trauma trigger''' is an experience that causes someone to recall a previous [[psychological trauma|traumatic]] [[memory]], although the trigger itself need not be frightening or traumatic and can be indirectly or superficially reminiscent an earlier traumatic incident.  Trauma triggers are related to [[posttraumatic stress disorder]] (PTSD), a condition in which people often cannot control the recurrence of emotional or physical symptoms,<ref name=\"Kolk1994\">{{cite journal | last = Kolk | first = Bessel van der | author-link = Bessel van der Kolk | title = The body keeps the score: memory and the evolving psychobiology of posttraumatic stress | journal = [[Harvard Review of Psychiatry]] | volume = 1 | issue = 5 | pages = 253\u2013265 | publisher = [[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins]] | pmid = 9384857 | date = July 2015 | url = http://www.trauma-pages.com/a/vanderk4.php | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref> or of [[repressed memory]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Post-traumatic stress disorder, a real illness | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071015184748/http://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/publications/post-traumatic-stress-disorder-a-real-illness/complete-publication.shtml#pub4 | archive-date = 15 October 2007 | url = http://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/publications/post-traumatic-stress-disorder-a-real-illness/complete-publication.shtml#pub4 | website = nimh.nih.gov | publisher = [[National Institute of Mental Health]] | date = 11 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>Herman, pp. 37, 42.</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Post traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) | url = http://www.vvaa.org.au/ptsd.htm | website = vvaa.org.au | publisher = Vietnam Veterans Association of Australia | date = 2015 | access-date = 4 February 2016 }}</ref> Triggers can be subtle and difficult to anticipate,<ref name=\"Kolk1994\"/><ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer | title = Post traumatic stress disorders in rape survivors | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151016165948/http://www.survive.org.uk/ptsd.html | archive-date = 16 October 2015 | url = http://www.survive.org.uk/ptsd.html | website = survive.org.uk | publisher = Survive | location = UK | date = 2015 }}</ref> and can sometimes exacerbate PTSD. A trauma trigger may also be referred to as a trauma stimulus or a trauma stressor.<ref name=Fagan/>\n\n==Visual media==\nIt has been suggested that the realistic portrayal of graphic violence in visual media may cause sufferers to encounter lifelike trauma triggers while watching movies or television.<ref name=Ephron/>\n\n==Trigger warnings==\n{{POV|section|date=November 2016}}\n{{Redirect|Trigger warning|the Knife Party album|Trigger Warning (Knife Party album)}}\nTrigger warnings are warnings that a work contains writing, images, or concepts which could act as a trauma trigger.<ref name=\"bbc ouch\">{{cite news | work =Ouch blog |title= Trigger warnings: What do they do?|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-ouch-26295437 |publisher=[[BBC]]|date= 25 February 2014|accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref> The term and concept originated on the [[Internet]] and then spread to other areas, such as print media and university courses.<ref name=\"bbc ouch\" />\n\nIn an interview about trigger warnings for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]],'' Professor Metin Basoglu, a psychologist internationally recognised for his trauma research, said that \"instead of encouraging a culture of avoidance, [the media] should be encouraging exposure. Most trauma survivors avoid situations that remind them of the experience. Avoidance means helplessness and helplessness means depression. That's not good.\"<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news | last = Waters | first = Florence | title = Trigger warnings: more harm than good? | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/11106670/Trigger-warnings-more-harm-than-good.html | work = [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | publisher = [[Telegraph Media Group]] | date = 4 October 2014 | access-date = 4 February 2016 }}</ref> Richard J. McNally, a Professor of Psychology at Harvard University, wrote in the ''Pacific Standard''<ref>{{cite news | last = McNally | first = Richard J. | title = Hazards ahead: the problem with trigger warnings, according to the research | url = http://www.psmag.com/navigation/health-and-behavior/hazards-ahead-problem-trigger-warnings-according-research-81946 | work = [[Pacific Standard]] | publisher = [[Sara Miller McCune]] | date = 20 May 2014 }}</ref> that \"trigger warnings are designed to help survivors avoid reminders of their trauma, thereby preventing emotional discomfort. Yet avoidance reinforces PTSD. Conversely, systematic exposure to triggers and the memories they provoke is the most effective means of overcoming the disorder.\" McNally's article cites several academic studies of PTSD sufferers in support of these claims.\n\nNow that trigger warnings have appeared in other media, [[Jay Caspian Kang]], best known for his sports writing at [[Grantland]], accused these warnings of \"reducing a work of literature to its ugliest plot points\".<ref>{{cite news | last = Caspian Kang | first = Jay | title = Trigger warnings and the novelists mind | url = http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/books/2014/05/trigger-warnings-and-the-novelists-mind.html | work = [[The New Yorker]] | publisher = [[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] | date = May 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===In higher education===\n\nStudents at [[UC Santa Barbara]] passed a resolution in support of mandatory trigger warnings for classes that could contain potentially upsetting material. Professors would be required to alert students of such material and allow them to skip classes that could make them feel uncomfortable.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jarvie|first=Jenny |title=Trigger happy|url=http://www.newrepublic.com/article/116842/trigger-warnings-have-spread-blogs-college-classes-thats-bad|work=[[The New Republic]]|publisher=[[Chris Hughes]]|date=3 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Association of University Professors]] has issued a report critical of trigger warnings in university contexts, stating that \"The presumption that students need to be protected rather than challenged in a classroom is at once infantilizing and anti-intellectual.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=On Trigger Warnings |publisher=[[American Association of University Professors]] |url=https://www.aaup.org/report/trigger-warnings |date=August 2014}}</ref>  Angus Johnston, a history professor at the [[City University of New York]], said that trigger warnings can be a part of \"sound [[pedagogy]],\" noting that students encountering potentially triggering material are \"coming to it as whole people with a wide range of experiences, and that the journey we're going on together may at times be painful. It's not coddling them to acknowledge that. In fact, it's just the opposite.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Johnston | first = Angus | title = Trigger warnings: a professor explains why he's pro-trigger warnings | work = [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] | url = http://www.slate.com/articles/life/inside_higher_ed/2014/05/hostos_community_college_professor_angus_johnston_explains_why_trigger_warnings.2.html | publisher = [[The Slate Group]] | date = May 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{wiktionary|Appendix:Glossary of traumatology}}\n<!-- New links in alphabetical order please}} -->\n* [[Acute stress reaction]]\n* [[Emotional dysregulation]]\n* [[Flashback (psychology)]]\n* [[Hypervigilance]]\n* [[Repressed memory]]\n* [[Survivor guilt]]\n* ''[[The Triggering]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=Ephron>{{cite news |last=Ephron |first=Dan |title=Battlefield flashbacks | work = [[Newsweek]] |publisher=Newsweek LLC |date=1 October 2006 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_kmnew/is_200610/ai_n16942632 |accessdate=20 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Fagan>{{cite journal | last1 = Fagan | first1 = Nancy | last2 = Freme | first2 = Kathleen | title = Confronting posttraumatic stress disorder | journal = Nursing | volume = 34 | issue = 2 | pages = 52\u201353 | publisher = [[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins]] | pmid = 14758331 | date = February 2004 | url = http://journals.lww.com/nursing/Abstract/2004/02000/Confronting_posttraumatic_stress_disorder.48.aspx | ref = harv | postscript = . | doi=10.1097/00152193-200402000-00048}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Herman |first=Judith Lewis, MD |title=Trauma and Recovery |publisher=BasicBooks, A Division of HarperCollins Publishers |year=1992 |isbn=9780465087655}}\n*{{cite news | last = Ouch blog |title= Trigger warnings: What do they do?|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-ouch-26295437 | work = [[BBC news]] |publisher=[[BBC]]|date= 25 February 2014|accessdate=25 February 2014}}\n* {{cite journal | last = Pozo | first = Diana | title = Trigger warnings and the porn studies classroom | journal = [[Porn Studies]] | volume = 2 | issue = 2\u20133 | pages = 286\u2013289 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/23268743.2015.1054683 | date = July 2015 | url = http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/23268743.2015.1054683 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}\n\n[[Category:Psychiatric models]]\n[[Category:Psychiatric terminology]]"}]}}}}